A '''gas hydrate pingo''' (GHP) is a submarine [[dome (geology)|dome structure]] formed by the accumulation [[gas hydrate]]s under the [[seafloor]]. Gas hydrate pingos resemble the [[pingo]] landforms found on land in [[periglacial]] regions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Serov |first1=Pavel |last2=Vadakkepuliyambatta |first2=Sunil |last3=Mienert |first3=Jürgen|last4=Patton |first4=Henry|last5=Portnov |first5=Alexey |last6=Silyakova |first6=Anna |last7=Panieri |first7=Guiliana |last8=Carroll |first8=Michael L.|last9=Carrol |first9=JoLyn|last10=Andreassen |first10=Karin|last11=Hubbard |first11=Alun|date=2017 |title=Postglacial response of Arctic Ocean gas hydrates to climatic amelioration |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/114/24/6215 |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=114 |issue=25 |pages=6215–6220 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1619288114 |access-date= }}</ref>
Gas hydrate pingo may accumulate non-hydrate gas under pressure leading to explosions that forms craters. Crater depressions of this type have been found on the seafloor of [[Barents Sea]]. The trigger for the explosions may be drop in pressure as result of lowering of the [[sea level]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.geoforskning.no/nyheter/grunnforskning/1838-forventer-utblasning-2018 |title=Forventer utblåsning |last=Setså |first=Ronny|language=Norwegian |date=2018 |website=geoforskning.no |publisher= |access-date=August 20, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>
A study in the [[Norwegian Sea]] found that gas hydrate pingoes were covered by [[bacterial mat]]s and that [[Polychaete]] [[tubeworm]]s that are associated with [[methane]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hovland |first1=Martin |last2=Svensen |first2=Henrik |date=2006 |title=Submarine pingoes: Indicators of shallow gas hydrates in a pockmark at Nyegga, Norwegian Sea |url= |journal=[[Marine Geology (journal)|Marine Geology]] |volume=228 |issue= |pages=15–23 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>
